{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "A quick outside view of artificial intelligence: what it is, where it shows up, why people care, and what kinds of questions and work sit behind it. This chapter makes AI feel concrete before the course gets technical.",
    "title": "Why artificial intelligence matters"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "AI is not one single machine mind. It is a group of methods for finding patterns, making predictions, generating text or images, and helping machines act in messy situations. This lesson gives a simple picture of what counts as AI and what does not.",
      "title": "What AI is actually doing"
    },
    {
      "description": "Recommendation feeds, maps, spam filters, voice assistants, fraud checks, captioning, and chatbots all rely on AI in different ways. Seeing these everyday examples makes the field feel less abstract and shows how often people already interact with it.",
      "title": "Where AI shows up in daily life"
    },
    {
      "description": "One striking idea in AI is that a system can become useful not because it was given every rule, but because it found patterns in large amounts of data. That shift from hand-written rules to learned behavior is one of the big reasons AI feels powerful and surprising.",
      "title": "Why pattern-finding changed everything"
    },
    {
      "description": "AI can save time, widen access, and help with hard problems, but it can also be wrong, biased, opaque, or misused. The field matters partly because its limits are as important as its strengths, especially when AI affects decisions about people.",
      "title": "Why AI needs judgment, not hype"
    },
    {
      "description": "People work with AI as researchers, engineers, product builders, designers, policy writers, teachers, healthcare teams, artists, and founders. The full course will give you the ideas behind these roles, from how systems learn to how to judge whether they are reliable and useful.",
      "title": "Who builds with AI and where this course goes"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Um primeiro olhar para a Biologia como o estudo da vida: como os seres vivos funcionam, mudam, interagem e dependem uns dos outros. Este capítulo mostra por que a Biologia aparece no corpo, na alimentação, na saúde, no ambiente e nas tecnologias atuais, e prepara o caminho para os temas que virão no curso.",
    "title": "Por que a vida funciona do jeito que funciona"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Biologia não é só decorar nomes de partes do corpo ou espécies. Ela busca explicar o que faz algo estar vivo, como os organismos crescem, se reproduzem, respondem ao ambiente e mantêm seu equilíbrio. É uma forma de olhar para plantas, animais, micróbios e seres humanos como partes de uma mesma história da vida.",
      "title": "O que a Biologia estuda de verdade"
    },
    {
      "description": "Uma das ideias mais marcantes da Biologia é que formas de vida muito diferentes compartilham soluções parecidas. A mesma lógica aparece em células, genes, energia e adaptação. Isso permite ligar uma ferida cicatrizando, uma floresta se renovando e uma bactéria resistindo a remédios dentro de um mesmo campo de ideias.",
      "title": "A unidade escondida por trás da diversidade"
    },
    {
      "description": "Biologia aparece quando você dorme mal, toma vacina, escolhe alimentos, cuida de uma planta ou ouve falar de epidemias e clima. Ela ajuda a pensar sobre saúde, envelhecimento, fertilidade, nutrição, conservação da natureza e até produtos que usamos no dia a dia. Não é um assunto distante: ele atravessa decisões comuns o tempo todo.",
      "title": "Onde a Biologia aparece no dia a dia"
    },
    {
      "description": "Quem trabalha com Biologia pode observar microrganismos, analisar DNA, acompanhar animais, estudar doenças, proteger ecossistemas, desenvolver técnicas em laboratório ou atuar com educação e divulgação científica. Também há espaço em saúde, meio ambiente, agricultura, biotecnologia e pesquisa. É um campo com muitos jeitos de participar, em laboratório, em campo ou com dados.",
      "title": "O que as pessoas fazem com esse conhecimento"
    },
    {
      "description": "No restante do curso, você vai passar das grandes perguntas para os mecanismos: células, hereditariedade, evolução, fisiologia, ecologia e relações entre seres vivos. Em vez de ver a vida como uma coleção de fatos soltos, você vai começar a perceber padrões que conectam corpo, ambiente e história natural.",
      "title": "Como o curso aprofunda esse olhar"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "A quick look at what quantum mechanics is really for: describing matter, light, atoms, and tiny events that shape the modern world. You’ll see why it feels strange, where it appears in everyday technology, and what kinds of questions and work it leads to before the main course gets technical.",
    "title": "Why quantum mechanics changed how we see reality"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Quantum mechanics studies how matter and light behave at very small scales. In that world, particles act unlike tiny billiard balls: outcomes come in chunks, measurement matters, and certainty gives way to probabilities. This lesson frames the field as a new set of rules for nature, not just a harder version of classical physics.",
      "title": "What quantum mechanics is really about"
    },
    {
      "description": "One of the field’s most striking ideas is that a quantum system can have several possible outcomes built into it at once, yet a measurement gives one result. That sounds bizarre, but it is also a practical way to predict experiments with incredible accuracy. The weirdness is not a side note; it is part of why the theory works.",
      "title": "Why the quantum world feels so strange"
    },
    {
      "description": "Quantum mechanics is behind lasers, semiconductors, MRI scanners, LEDs, atomic clocks, and much of modern electronics. Even if you never work in a physics lab, the field helps explain the devices, materials, and communication systems woven into ordinary life. This lesson connects the tiny world to familiar tools and industries.",
      "title": "Where quantum mechanics shows up in real life"
    },
    {
      "description": "People use quantum mechanics in research, engineering, chemistry, materials science, nanotechnology, and emerging quantum computing. Some build better sensors or chips, some model molecules, and some test deep questions about nature itself. This lesson shows the kinds of roles, projects, and communities connected to the field.",
      "title": "What people do with quantum mechanics"
    },
    {
      "description": "The full course will move from the big picture into the core ideas that make quantum mechanics usable: states, measurements, wave functions, uncertainty, and simple systems like particles and atoms. You do not need to accept the strangeness all at once. Step by step, the course will turn surprising claims into a framework you can actually work with.",
      "title": "How the full course goes deeper"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "A quick look at how civil courts turn everyday disputes into decisions. You’ll see what civil procedure actually does, why rules about timing, notice, evidence, and fairness matter, and how this course will help you read lawsuits as a system rather than a blur of paperwork.",
    "title": "How civil cases move through court"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Civil procedure is the rulebook for non-criminal cases: who can sue, where a case belongs, what must be filed, how each side gets notice, and how a dispute reaches judgment or settlement. The subject is less about dramatic courtroom speeches and more about the structure that makes a case possible at all.",
      "title": "What civil procedure is really doing"
    },
    {
      "description": "A case can change direction because of something that sounds small: the wrong court, late service, a missed deadline, or a complaint that leaves out a key fact. Civil procedure shows how power in litigation often comes from sequence and timing, not just from who seems morally right.",
      "title": "Why procedure can decide the case"
    },
    {
      "description": "Questions from civil procedure show up far beyond law school. They affect consumer lawsuits, workplace claims, medical disputes, class actions, online platform cases, and fights over where a case should be heard. These rules shape access to courts, litigation costs, delay, privacy, and pressure to settle.",
      "title": "Where these rules shape everyday life"
    },
    {
      "description": "Lawyers, judges, clerks, mediators, policy advocates, and in-house legal teams all rely on procedural thinking. Some people draft pleadings and motions, some manage discovery, some design fairer court systems, and some study whether the rules help ordinary people use the courts. Civil procedure connects legal writing, strategy, public institutions, and reform.",
      "title": "Who uses civil procedure at work"
    },
    {
      "description": "In the full course, you’ll go step by step through jurisdiction, pleadings, motions, discovery, joinder, summary judgment, trial, and preclusion. The goal is to make the life of a civil case feel predictable enough that you can see why each stage exists and how the pieces fit together.",
      "title": "How the full course goes deeper"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Una mirada rápida a cómo el urbanismo organiza calles, viviendas, transporte, espacios públicos y servicios para que la vida en la ciudad funcione mejor. Verás por qué decisiones que parecen invisibles cambian tiempos de viaje, seguridad, convivencia, comercio y ambiente, y cómo este curso te dará herramientas para leer y pensar la ciudad con más criterio.",
    "title": "La ciudad como diseño de la vida diaria"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "El urbanismo no trata solo de edificios bonitos ni de hacer planos. Se ocupa de cómo se acomodan personas, actividades, movilidad, naturaleza e infraestructura en un mismo lugar, y de qué reglas ayudan o estorban para vivir bien en la ciudad.",
      "title": "Qué hace realmente el urbanismo"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una banqueta ancha, una esquina mal resuelta, un parque cercano o una parada de bus bien ubicada pueden cambiar rutinas completas. El urbanismo influye en cuánto tiempo tardas, cuánto gastas, qué tan seguro te sientes y con quién te encuentras en el camino.",
      "title": "Cómo la ciudad afecta tu día a día"
    },
    {
      "description": "Dos calles con la misma longitud pueden sentirse totalmente distintas: una invita a caminar y quedarse; otra empuja a irse rápido. La mezcla de usos, la sombra, la escala, el ruido y la conectividad hacen que una ciudad no solo funcione, sino que también se sienta habitable.",
      "title": "Por qué algunos lugares se sienten vivos"
    },
    {
      "description": "El urbanismo aparece en decisiones sobre vivienda, transporte, espacio público, riesgo, acceso a servicios y crecimiento urbano. Por eso importa para gobiernos, vecindarios, diseño, salud, sostenibilidad, datos, participación ciudadana y proyectos que buscan ciudades más justas y prácticas.",
      "title": "Dónde importa y quién trabaja en esto"
    },
    {
      "description": "En el curso irás pasando de mirar la ciudad como usuario a leerla como sistema. Vas a ganar lenguaje y criterios para notar patrones, comparar decisiones urbanas y pensar por qué ciertos barrios, calles y servicios funcionan mejor que otros.",
      "title": "Cómo este curso te ayudará a mirar mejor la ciudad"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Un premier regard sur l’histoire de l’art : ce qu’elle observe, pourquoi les images et les objets comptent, et comment ce domaine relie beauté, pouvoir, croyances et vie quotidienne. De quoi voir les œuvres autrement avant d’entrer dans les périodes, les styles et les méthodes du cours.",
    "title": "Pourquoi l’histoire de l’art change notre regard"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "L’histoire de l’art ne consiste pas seulement à reconnaître des tableaux célèbres. Elle s’intéresse à ce que les humains fabriquent pour montrer, convaincre, prier, décorer, impressionner, raconter ou se souvenir. Une fresque, une statue, une affiche ou un bâtiment peuvent tous devenir des indices sur une époque et sur les personnes qui l’ont vécue.",
      "title": "Ce que l’histoire de l’art regarde vraiment"
    },
    {
      "description": "Une œuvre ne parle pas seulement de goût. Elle peut montrer qui détient le pouvoir, quelles idées circulent, ce qu’une société admire, craint ou cache. Un portrait officiel, une cathédrale ou une publicité n’agissent pas de la même façon, mais chacun cherche à produire un effet sur ceux qui le regardent.",
      "title": "Les œuvres montrent aussi le pouvoir et les idées"
    },
    {
      "description": "L’histoire de l’art n’est pas enfermée dans les musées. Elle aide à regarder autrement les rues, les monuments, les objets, les images sur écran, les logos, la mode ou l’aménagement d’un lieu. Elle donne des mots pour décrire ce qu’on voit et pour remarquer que les formes influencent nos émotions et nos habitudes sans qu’on s’en rende toujours compte.",
      "title": "Pourquoi cela compte dans la vie de tous les jours"
    },
    {
      "description": "On peut rencontrer l’histoire de l’art dans les musées, le patrimoine, la médiation culturelle, l’édition, l’enseignement, les expositions, les archives, le marché de l’art ou encore la restauration. On peut aussi s’en servir dans des projets plus larges, dès qu’il faut lire des images, raconter des objets ou relier culture et société.",
      "title": "Où ce domaine mène concrètement"
    },
    {
      "description": "La suite du cours donnera des repères solides pour situer les grandes périodes, distinguer des styles, comparer des œuvres et poser de bonnes questions devant une image ou un monument. Peu à peu, le regard devient plus précis : on ne voit plus seulement “quelque chose de beau”, mais des choix, des codes et des histoires.",
      "title": "Ce que la suite du cours va apporter"
    }
  ]
}
